    <div class="blog-content content-entryindent ">
        "Dude, you're setting a trap?  No fair having fun without me." Scrap said as I heard him take a drag off of his cigarette on the other end of the phone.<br/><br/>"Yep, it's going to get interesting around here.  Look, I may need to bring you into this shortly.  Clear your schedule." I demanded.<br/><br/>"Aw, man!  I hate flying!" Scrap whined as he disconnected from our call.  There's just no making that guy happy aside from a carton of cigarettes a week and a new Zippo lighter every Christmas.<br/><br/>I had taken over a small conference room as my work area and was in the process of completing my risk assessment of Huge Kingdom.  <br/><br/>"Interesting." I said to myself as I examined the event timeline that MMM had provided me.  <br/><br/>Huge Kingdom had one of the largest MMORPG launches in gaming history recently (in terms of advertising dollars spent) and ironically enough, the server disturbances had started to occur within 48 hours of the game launch.  Perhaps someone was finding it too hard to play by the rules? <br/><br/>The game network was amazing.  Large mainframe computers were the "brains" of Huge Kingdom handling all computation work, statistics tracking, etc.  The HK clients were "dumb" and performed no game-critical calculations except for firing the game image onto the player's screen and taking keyboard and mouse commands.  Communication between the clients and the servers were encrypted with a strange byte-code method that I hadn't seen before.  The encryption technology was called "QuickCrypter" and was a home-grown encryption solution.<br/><br/>I glanced over the server logs regarding every recorded server event and circled some that caught my eye:<br/><br/><i><br/><b>June 7th</b> - player X took gold from a chest that was 3000 miles away from him<br/><br/><b>June 8th</b> - player X had an out-of-bounds conversation with a character 5000 <br/>miles away from him<br/><br/><b>June 9th</b> - player Y complains to technical support that his gold inventory went from 500,000 to 0 in a matter of seconds<br/><br/><b>June 9th</b> - player Z complains that an expensive magical weapon disappeared from his inventory.  Player Z was later killed by Player X who was wielding the very same weapon<br/></i><br/>Player X always connected from a different IP address.<br/><br/>A few moments later, my eyes widened with disbelief.  <br/><br/>Player X had approximately 50 violations a day recorded on the server and played every day.<br/><br/>But why hadn't MMM employees gone through the logs and looked for this information?  The programmers had the foresight to include boundary checking in the game.  Perhaps this case wasn't going to be very challenging after all. <br/><br/>A knock at the conference room door startled me.<br/><br/>"Chief?" a voice said as the door opened.  It was one of the MMM employees assigned to help me with the case, Ken Banobi.  <br/><br/>"Hey Ken, what's up?" I asked as I glanced back down at the server logs.<br/><br/>"We're all ready to go, just waiting on you to join us in the room." Ken replied.<br/><br/>"Join you?  For what?" I replied, still concentrating on the log files before me.<br/><br/><i>"Your trap is ready."</i> 
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer"></div>
    <div class="marginleftgutter">
